<DOC><DOCNO> AP880222-0090 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 1057EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Salvador-Strike     02-22 0213</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Salvador-Strike,0220</SECOND><HEAD>Transport Strike Called By Guerillas Halts Bus Traffic</HEAD><DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A 24-hour transport strikecalled by leftist guerrillas virtually halted bus and truck traffictoday and drastically curtailed use of automobiles.   The strike was called by members of the Farabundo Marti NationalLiberation Front to protest legislative and municipal electionsscheduled for March 20. The rebels say the elections are a farce.   No buses circulated in this capital of 1 million people.Thousands of people walked to work, although some pickup trucksjammed with passengers were on the roads.   The army said it doubled motorized patrols to provide securityfor people who defied the strike.   The private radio station YSU said truck and bus trafficnationwide was about 5 percent of normal. From the westernprovincial capital of Santa Ana, the radio reported that thestoppage of buses was total.   It said two buses of 50 that normally would have been dispatchedleft the eastern provincial capital of San Miguel for other cities.   The leftist guerrillas have been fighting the U.S.-backedgovernment since 1979 with a campaign that includes economicsabotage.   There were seven guerrilla-imposed transport strikes last year.Three strike violators were killed, about 30 were wounded and some160 vehicles were destroyed or damaged.</TEXT></DOC>